Former Pakistan Prime Minister Imran Khan was taken into custody by paramilitary forces from Islamabad High Court premises today. The arrest of Mr Khan has led to a call from his party for nationwide protests, presenting another blow to the nuclear-armed country struggling with an economic crisis.

Chaos prevailed in Pakistan after former Prime Minister Imran Khan was arrested by paramilitary rangers on Tuesday while he was present at the Islamabad High Court for the hearing of a corruption case. Workers of Imran Khan's party, Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI), took to streets after his arrest and even reached Pakistan Army's headquarters in Rawalpindi, resulting in the imposition of Section 144 across the country. Stay on this page for latest updates and developments.

PTI supporters set ablaze Radio Pakistan office in Peshawar after Imran Khan's arrest

Supporters of former Pakistan Prime Minister Imran Khan and PTI chief on Tuesday put on fire the building of Radio Pakistan in Peshawar after latter's arrest from outside Islamabad High Court by Pakistan Rangers. Supporters have took to streets in various cities of the neighbouring country demanding Khan's release.

Imran Khan Arrest Live Updates: Protests intensified in several cities in Pakistan over former Pakistan Prime Minister Imran Khan‚Äôs arrest from outside the Islamabad High Court (IHC) on Tuesday. The protests are underway in cities, including Lahore, Peshawar, Karachi, Gilgit, Karak, according to the official Twitter handle of Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf party (PTI). While some of the PTI supporters, demanding Khan‚Äôs release, entered the General Headquarters (of the Pakistan Army) in Rawalpindi, others, according to Pakistan media reports, entered the residence of Lahore Corps Commander and vandalised his house, hours after Khan‚Äôs arrest.

Meanwhile, Chief Justice at the Islamabad High Court (IHC) Aamer Farooq Tuesday took strong exception over the arrest taking place at the IHC premises, following Khan‚Äôs arrest, earlier in the day, from outside the court, Dawn reported. The additional attorney general retorted whether the parking lot and other areas of the IHC should be considered the same as the courtroom, the Dawn report said. Poonch Terror Attack: Latest developments and details uncovered

Five Indian Army soldiers lost their lives in an attack by terrorists in the Rajouri district of Jammu and Kashmir on April 20, 2023. The attackers fired bullets and threw grenades at the Army truck, which caught fire. The area has been cordoned off and a search operation is underway to find the perpetrators. The terrorist group, People's Anti Fascist Front, an offshoot of Jaish-e-Mohammed, has claimed responsibility for the attack. A 7.62 mm steel-core bullet made in China was found at the site.

India 'retaliates' after pro-Khalistan attacks; Halts trade talks with United Kingdom

India is up in arms over the UK government's inaction towards attacks on the Indian Embassy. New Delhi has reportedly halted trade talks with the United Kingdom. According to a report by The Times, India will not continue the trade talks until the UK government condemns the Khalistani Group that attacked the Indian Embassy in March. The Times report added that to restart the negotiation, the UK Home Office is planning to crack down on the Sikh extremists and supporters of the Khalistani movement.

Pakistan PM in Toshakhana case live updates: Pakistan court cancels arrest warrants for Imran Khan in Toshakhana case

Live Update - Pakistan court on Saturday cancelled arrest warrants for Imran Khan in Toshakhana case. Turkey Syria earthquake : New-born and mother saved after four days in rubble

A Turkish Father Refused To Let Go Of His Dead 15-Year-Old Daughter's Hand

His daughter, Irmak, was dead. But he refused to let her go, caressing the fingers peeking out from a mattress the girl was asleep on when the first pre-dawn tremor struck.

Turkey, Syria Earthquake Live Updates : 6 people pulled alive from rubble ; toll crosses 22,000

Turkey, Syria Earthquake Live Updates: The rescue of several survivors from the rubble of buildings in Turkey lifted the spirits of weary search crews on Friday, four days after a major earthquake struck the country and neighbouring Syria, killing at least 21,500 people. Cold, hunger and despair gripped hundreds of thousands of people left homeless by the tremors, the deadliest in the region for decades. Several people were rescued from the rubble of buildings during the night, including a 10-year-old boy saved with his mother after 90 hours in the Samandag district of Hatay province. Also in Hatay, a seven-year-old girl named Asya Donmez was rescued after 95 hours and taken to hospital, the state-owned Anadolu news agency reported. But hopes were fading that many more would be found alive in the ruins of thousands of collapsed buildings in towns and cities across the region. It now ranks as seventh most deadly natural disaster this century, ahead of Japan's 2011 tremor and tsunami and approaching the 31,000 killed by a quake in neighbouring Iran in 2003. Stay with TOI for all updates

Pakistan Mosque blast Live Updates: 46 killed, 150 hurt at mosque in Pakistan's Peshawar

Peshawar blast Live Updates: A Taliban suicide bomber blew himself up in a mosque packed with worshippers during afternoon prayers on Monday in the high-security zone in Pakistan's northwestern Peshawar city, killing at least 46 people and wounding more than 100 others, mostly policemen, security and health officials said. The blast occurred inside the mosque in the Police Lines area around 1.40 pm when worshippers, which included personnel of the police, army and bomb disposal squad - were offering the Zuhr (afternoon) prayers. The bomber who was present in the front row blew himself up, officials said. Lady Reading Hospital officials said 46 people have died so far. However, the Peshawar Police has released a list of 38 victims. There were mostly policemen among the injured. A brother of the slain commander of the Tehreek-e-Taliban Pakistan (TTP) Umar Khalid Khurasani claimed that the suicide attack was part of the revenge attack for his brother who was killed last August in Afghanistan. The outlawed TTP, known as the Pakistani Taliban, has carried out a number of suicide attacks in the past, targeting security personnel. Superintendent of Police (Investigation), Peshawar, Shazad Kaukab, whose office is close to the mosque, told the media that the blast occurred when he just entered the mosque to offer prayers. He said he luckily survived the attack.

description:
Pakistan is a classic case study of a nation which has repeatedly shot itself in the foot. In a never ending vicious cycle, Pakistan takes a loan and then takes another, simply to pay back the interest on the loan.

Lt Gen Syed Ata Hasnain (Retd) and Major Gaurav Arya (Retd) discuss.

title: ‡§ï‡•ç‡§Ø‡•ã‡§Ç ‡§™‡•Ä‡§õ‡•á ‡§≠‡§æ‡§ó‡§æ ‡§ö‡•Ä‡§® ?LAC ‡§ï‡§æ ‡§∏‡§ö
description:
China initiated disengagement along the LAC. It is moving back and so is the Indian Army. Status Quo Ante is being restored. This means that both armies are moving back to the pre April 2020 positions.

But can China be trusted? What is the guarantee that it will not try a similar misadventure again? 

Let‚Äôs talk to Lt Gen Vinod Bhatia (Retd), former Director General Military Operations (DGMO) of the Indian Army and find out the details.
